ACT III. SCENE IV.

Simo orders Davus to be called, to satisfy Chremes that Pamphilus and Glycerium were at varianoe, and that the former was now willing to take a wife. Davus having no suspicion of what had happened, but secure that no marriage was intended, is of himself coming out to have the pleasure of bantering Simo a little, when, to his great mortification, he learns the ill success of his project, and is thrown into the greatest perplexity. He dissembles, however, his concern as much as possible before the old man ; and Chremes, imagining that all is well, returns home to give the proper orders.
